    <b>Prevalence:</b> In 2008, there were 12.7 million new cancer cases worldwide and 7.6 million cancer deaths. In economically developed countries, the most common types of cancer are prostate, lung, and colorectal cancers in men, and breast, colorectal, and lung cancers in women. In economically developing countries, cancers of the lung, stomach, and liver were most prevalent in men, and breast, cervical, and lung cancers were more frequently found in women. Breast cancer has now become the leading cause of cancer deaths in women in developing countries, representing 22% of all cancers among African women. Other cancer types that are pressing concerns in Africa are cervix, liver, Kaposi sarcoma, and urinary bladder cancers that come from infectious agents
